<section class="card">
  <h2>What Space Is Best For</h2>

  <p>
    Space is best for gardeners who want smooth spinach leaves for fresh use, cooking, and repeat harvests.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is a practical spinach, but it still needs cool timing. Do not expect it to behave like a summer green.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Is Space Good for Short Seasons?</h2>

  <p>
    Spinach is a strong short-season crop because it grows in cool weather and can be harvested young.
  </p>

  <p>
    The hard part is heat and day length. Spinach can bolt quickly when days get long and temperatures rise.
  </p>

  <p>
    Short-season gardeners often get the best results from early spring sowings and late-summer or fall sowings rather than midsummer plantings.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>When to Plant Space</h2>

  <p>
    Direct sow spinach early in spring once soil can be worked. Spinach prefers cool conditions and does not need warm soil like beans or cucumbers.
  </p>

  <p>
    For fall crops, sow late enough to avoid the worst heat but early enough for leaves to size before cold and low light slow growth.
  </p>

  <p>
    For local timing, use the <a href="https://growbydate.com/crops/spinach/">spinach growing guide</a> and your frost dates. Spinach timing is about cool windows, not summer heat.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Grow Space</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Sow in cool weather:</strong> Spinach germinates and grows best before heat builds.</li>
    <li><strong>Keep soil moist:</strong> Dry soil can reduce germination and speed stress.</li>
    <li><strong>Thin for leaf size:</strong> Baby spinach can be tighter than mature plants.</li>
    <li><strong>Use succession sowings:</strong> Small repeat sowings give a steadier harvest.</li>
    <li><strong>Harvest before bolting:</strong> Once spinach sends a flower stalk, leaf quality drops.</li>
    <li><strong>Use shade if needed:</strong> Shade cloth can help during warm spells.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Harvest and Use</h2>

  <p>
    Harvest spinach as baby leaves, individual outer leaves, or whole plants depending on spacing and timing.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pick while leaves are tender and before plants bolt. In warm weather, spinach can move from perfect to past-prime quickly.
  </p>

  <p>
    Use spinach fresh, cooked, or frozen. Cool harvested leaves quickly for better texture.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Growing Space</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Planting too late in spring:</strong> Heat and long days can trigger bolting.</li>
    <li><strong>Letting seedbeds dry out:</strong> Spinach germination can be uneven without moisture.</li>
    <li><strong>Expecting midsummer quality:</strong> Spinach is not a heat-loving green.</li>
    <li><strong>Waiting for huge leaves:</strong> Young leaves are often the better harvest.</li>
    <li><strong>Skipping fall sowings:</strong> Fall can be one of the best spinach windows where timing allows.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Space vs Other Spinach Varieties</h2>

  <p>
    Compared with other spinach varieties, Space should be chosen for bolt tolerance, leaf type, and seasonal window. Some varieties are better for spring speed, while others hold quality longer in changing weather.
  </p>

  <p>
    For this crop, the better choice depends on what you want from the harvest. Space is worth growing when its maturity window, plant habit, and kitchen use match your garden better than a faster, larger, or more specialized alternative.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Who Should Grow Space?</h2>

  <p>
    Space is a good choice if you want quick cool-season greens and can plant before heat becomes dominant.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is less useful as a midsummer crop unless your climate is cool or you can provide shade and steady moisture.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Plan Around Your Local Season</h2>

  <p>
    Space can be a good choice when the timing matches your spring conditions, growing season length, and expected fall frost. The exact planting window still depends on where you garden.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before choosing a planting date, check your local frost window and crop timing. A variety can fit short seasons well and still underperform if it is planted too late, started too late indoors, or grown in poor conditions.
